<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-02-15T03:44:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-02-15T03:44:00-05:00" n="701" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d701">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">882.01 Foreign Control/53: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Vice Consul at Monrovia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wall</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-02-15T08:00:00-00:44">February 15, 1931—8
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 11:30 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>22. Attorney General Grimes, designated to collaborate with Sottile at
                            Geneva on slavery matters, sailed on S. S. <hi rend="italic">Sultan</hi>
                            of the German-African Line February 14th.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wall</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>